Have you tested this? I have calendars with mixed all-day and non-allday events, and the non-allday event start- and end datetimes are returned just fine, just localized to UTC.

The issue here is that, for all-day events, EWS will return the start- and end datetimes at midnight in the timezone we have requested, which I think is the best EWS can do without introducing even more weirdness. We're always requesting datetimes in UTC, which is unfortunate for all-day events if you're treating the datetimes at face value. I think we can live with this, as long as we can work around it with:

```python
for i in account.calendar.all():
    if i.is_all_day:
        print(i.start.date(), i.end.date())
    else:
        print(i.start, i.end)
```

If you prefer, we can add a workaround on the `CalendarItem` class that post-processes `start` and `end` values for allday events when received from the server.

Ah. That's probably not the one causing problem... It is probably this function:

```
/* result might be undefined when input_num is zero */
static inline int __builtin_clzll(unsigned long long input_num) {
    unsigned long index;
#ifdef _WIN64  // highly recommended!!!
    _BitScanReverse64(&index, input_num);
#else  // if we must support 32-bit Windows
    if (input_num > 0xFFFFFFF) {
        _BitScanReverse(&index, (uint32_t)(input_num >> 32));
    } else {
        _BitScanReverse(&index, (uint32_t)(input_num));
        index += 32;
    }
#endif
    return 63 - index;
}
```

