So if you look at the `process_event` code for the Text widget, you can see that it inserts characters by listening for any incoming ascii (not sure how that works on, say, a Korean keyboard, but it works for me so far). https://github.com/peterbrittain/asciimatics/blob/master/asciimatics/widgets.py#L1644. It also allows deletion by listening for the backspace and delete keys.

Just catch those events and ignore them in your process_event method like so:

    def process_event(self, event):
        if isinstance(event, KeyboardEvent):
            ...
            # disallow all editing
            elif event.key_code == Screen.KEY_BACK:
                return event
            elif event.key_code == Screen.KEY_DELETE:
                return event
            elif event.key_code >= 32:
                return event

This has the advantage that the user can still move the cursor around with the arrow keys to scroll the text if it's too long to fit in the space provided.

@bodgit I was thinking about your usecase and I can suggest you just split your class into two with inheritance:

```Python
@api.route('/bar', endpoint='bar')
class Bar(Resource):
    @api.doc(...)
    def get(self):
        ...

@api.route('/foo/bar', endpoint='foo')
class PostableBar(Bar):
    @api.doc(...)
    def post(self):
        ...
```

This seems to be an even cleaner solution and you don't need `methods=['GET']` at all.

